Optional Lab - Derivatives
This lab will give you a more intuitive understanding of derivatives. It will show you a simple way of calculating derivatives arithmetically. It will also introduce you to a handy Python library that allows you to calculate derivatives symbolically.

from sympy import symbols, diff
Informal definition of derivatives
The formal definition of derivatives can be a bit daunting with limits and values 'going to zero'. The idea is really much simpler.

The derivative of a function describes how the output of a function changes when there is a small change in an input variable.

Let's use the cost function ğ½(ğ‘¤)
 as an example. The cost ğ½
 is the output and ğ‘¤
 is the input variable.
Let's give a 'small change' a name epsilon or ğœ–
. We use these Greek letters because it is traditional in mathematics to use epsilon(ğœ–
) or delta (Î”
) to represent a small value. You can think of it as representing 0.001 or some other small value.

if ğ‘¤â†‘ğœ– causes ğ½(ğ‘¤)â†‘by ğ‘˜Ã—ğœ– thenâˆ‚ğ½(ğ‘¤)âˆ‚ğ‘¤=ğ‘˜(1)
This just says if you change the input to the function ğ½(ğ‘¤)
 by a little bit and the output changes by ğ‘˜
 times that little bit, then the derivative of ğ½(ğ‘¤)
 is equal to ğ‘˜
.

Let's try this out. Let's look at the derivative of the function ğ½(ğ‘¤)=ğ‘¤2
 at the point ğ‘¤=3
 and ğœ–=0.001
J = (3)**2
J_epsilon = (3 + 0.001)**2
k = (J_epsilon - J)/0.001    # difference divided by epsilon
print(f"J = {J}, J_epsilon = {J_epsilon}, dJ_dw ~= k = {k:0.6f} ")
We have increased the input value a little bit (0.001), causing the output to change from 9 to 9.006001, an increase of 6 times the input increase. Referencing (1) above, this says that ğ‘˜=6
, so âˆ‚ğ½(ğ‘¤)âˆ‚ğ‘¤â‰ˆ6
. If you are familiar with calculus, you know, written symbolically, âˆ‚ğ½(ğ‘¤)âˆ‚ğ‘¤=2ğ‘¤
. With ğ‘¤=3
 this is 6. Our calculation above is not exactly 6 because to be exactly correct ğœ–
 would need to be infinitesimally small or really, really small. That is why we use the symbols â‰ˆ
 or ~= rather than =. Let's see what happens if we make ğœ–
 smaller.

J = (3)**2
J_epsilon = (3 + 0.000000001)**2
k = (J_epsilon - J)/0.000000001
print(f"J = {J}, J_epsilon = {J_epsilon}, dJ_dw ~= k = {k} ")
The value gets close to exactly 6 as we reduce the size of ğœ–
. Feel free to try reducing the value further.

Finding symbolic derivatives
In backprop it is useful to know the derivative of simple functions at any input value. Put another way, we would like to know the 'symbolic' derivative rather than the 'arithmetic' derivative. An example of a symbolic derivative is, âˆ‚ğ½(ğ‘¤)âˆ‚ğ‘¤=2ğ‘¤
, the derivative of ğ½(ğ‘¤)=ğ‘¤2
 above. With the symbolic derivative you can find the value of the derivative at any input value ğ‘¤
.

If you have taken a calculus course, you are familiar with the many differentiation rules that mathematicians have developed to solve for a derivative given an expression. Well, it turns out this process has been automated with symbolic differentiation programs. An example of this in python is the SymPy library. Let's take a look at how to use this.

ğ½=ğ‘¤2
Define the python variables and their symbolic names.

J, w = symbols('J, w')
Define and print the expression. Note SymPy produces a latex string which generates a nicely readable equation.

J=w**2
J
Use SymPy's diff to differentiate the expression for ğ½
 with respect to ğ‘¤
. Note the result matches our earlier example.

dJ_dw = diff(J,w)
dJ_dw
Evaluate the derivative at a few points by 'substituting' numeric values for the symbolic values. In the first example, ğ‘¤
 is replaced by 2
.

dJ_dw.subs([(w,2)])    # derivative at the point w = 2
dJ_dw.subs([(w,3)])    # derivative at the point w = 3
dJ_dw.subs([(w,-3)])    # derivative at the point w = -3
ğ½=2ğ‘¤
w, J = symbols('w, J')
J = 2 * w
J
dJ_dw = diff(J,w)
dJ_dw
dJ_dw.subs([(w,-3)])    # derivative at the point w = -3
Compare this with the arithmetic calculation

J = 2*3
J_epsilon = 2*(3 + 0.001)
k = (J_epsilon - J)/0.001
print(f"J = {J}, J_epsilon = {J_epsilon}, dJ_dw ~= k = {k} ")
For the function ğ½=2ğ‘¤
, it is easy to see that any change in ğ‘¤
